sentence: The Dow Jones Industrial Average barely pulled off a positive close Tuesday as gains in the energy sector were nearly overshadowed by persistent pressure on tech stocks as Apple ( AAPL ) became defensive before the company releases its latest quarterly results on Wednesday.
The major benchmark indices returned early gains as eroding consumer confidence and investors' concerns about declining iPhone sales weighed on equity markets for most of the day.
Despite upbeat first quarter results from component stocks 3M ( MMM ) and Proctor & Gamble ( PG ), the Dow clung to the flat line, unable to make a convincing break of 18,000.
Today's economic data seemed to confirm Wall Street's expectation that the Federal Reserve will not make any changes to monetary policy at the end of tomorrow's policy meeting.
Durable goods orders increased 0.8% last month, but that was half of what analysts predicted.
And excluding transportation orders, orders for longer-lasting manufactured goods fell 0.2%, missing the estimated +0.5%.
The Conference Board's consumer confidence index declined by more-than-expected to 94.2 from March's downward revised 96.1, missing 96.0 expectations.
The Richmond Fed manufacturing index also declined, from 22.0 in March to 14.0 in April, but this was better than estimates for a decline to 12.0.
Additionally, the Case Shiller home price index increased an as-expected 0.7%, and the purchasing manager's preliminary services sector index for April rose to 52.1 from March's 51.3.

Here's where the markets stood at the close:

(+) AMID (+21.39%) Acquired interests in strategic Gulf of Mexico midstream infrastructure and incremental ownership in Delta House for about $225 million

(+) NVIV (+14.02%) Sixth patient implanted with neuro-spinal scaffold improved from AIS A spinal cord injury to incomplete AIS B spinal cord injury.

(-) SRPT (-26.29%) Federal advisory panel voted that Duchenne muscular dystrophy drug Eteplirsen was not effective
